Ukranian Coffee Shops: New Market Customer Segments

Donovan Doyle

9/28/2021

Using Google Reviews data, we can look at the existing coffee shops in Ukraine and identify the potential customer segments of coffee drinkers by area. Through our analysis, we have identified 4 customer segments, and what makes them different, to target as we expand into Ukraine. These four segments can be simplified as:

  • High-Quality
  • Convenience
  • Luxury
  • Hidden Gem

Summary Statistics: Understanding the Market

The coffee market analyzed is comprised of 10 different regions, with 20 coffee providers in each region. To examine the data, we will look at:

  1. The population make-up of each region
  2. The ratings of coffee shops within each region and their service offerings (delivery, dine-in service, takeout)
  3. How the coffee market may be different within each region
  4. How service options can potentially influence ratings

This data comes from the United Nations, World Population Review, and Wikipedia. It sets the framework for how each region is different from a population density perspective before we look at differences within the coffee markets in each.

Differences in the Region Ratings

In the table above, the true difference in rating between 4.78 and 4.55 is unclear, as both are high values on the rating scale of 1-5. We can compare the distributions of the highest rated regions with the lowest, which helps us understand there is a stark contrast between the ratings.

This shows that region will play a significant factor in how we segment our customers, as the coffee market is demonstrably stronger in both Kiev and Odessa compared to Kharkiv and Dnipro.

Summary Findings

Through this analysis, we can conclude:

  1. Geographic differences: There is variance in the regions population and population density, showing a potential opening for different customer segments based off of geography.
  2. Existing coffee competition:Some regions show a stronger coffee market with higher ratings, despite service offerings remaining roughly similar.
  3. Services dont matter:There is not a strong correlation in terms of services provided and rating.

Identifying Customer Segments: How Many and Who?

In our current market, we operate with 5 customer segments identified. As the market landscape can be drastically different in Ukraine, we must determine how many different customer segments there are, and what makes each segment distinct.

This plot doesnt have to be fully understood by the team. Through machine learning techniques, we can conclude that there are four customer segments to identify.

Well use a machine learning model called K-Means Clustering to segment the four groups. This will group the coffee shops from the Google Business Review data into four categories, based off of characteristics gathered about each.

The Four Customer Segments: the Model

While not important to fully grasp, its important to comment on our model. We didnt have outstanding results, but can still apply the model and learn from it. The ideal model would have four groups that were clearly distinct from each other and roughly the same size. We can see below this is not the case. Using a ratio that grades our model on a scale of 0 to 1, we achieved a ratio of 0.36, which leaves more to be desired.

One customer segment that is clearly differentiated is Segment C. Looking at the data, Segment C includes the four shops with an expensive price rating, which is an important factor when considering the customer. Segment C represents our expensive-taste coffee drinkers.

We need to look at other factors in order to determine what differentiates our remaining three segments.

This plot helps us identify what Segment A is: our high-rating coffee drinkers. These shops rate very highly, even if they dont necessarily have all of the service options available.

This leaves us with two groups left to identify: B and D.

There are two more areas we can look: review count and service options. We will use review count as a proxy for popularity; the more people who go to a coffee shop, the more likely the shop is to receive reviews.

Results

Instead of our typical five customer segments, we have identified four, characterized as follows:

  • Segment A: Quality Coffee Drinkers. This segment searches out the best coffee possible in densely populated areas, even if those shops dont have all the service features their competitors may have. The shops may be less-frequented, judging by the review information, but rate the highest by those who do try.

  • Segment B: Convenience Coffee Drinkers. This segment enjoys bustling, highly-frequented coffee shops with all the bells and whistlesthose that have delivery, dine-in, and takeout offerings.

  • Segment C: Luxury Coffee Drinkers. This segment is the smallest, but is attracted to high-class coffee shops that end up charging the most. They arent necessarily based in cities, as population density per shop is low, and arent necessarily rated the highest, but dont mind spending their money on coffee.

  • Segment D: Hidden Gem Coffee Drinkers. This segment enjoys the quieter, smaller shops. These shops are a bit more bare-bones, as none of them deliver, and arent quite as popular, but rate similar to those in segments B and C.

Future Initiatives and Limitations

As we continue to explore our expansion into Ukraine, we can fine-tune this model to fully develop our go-to market plan and see great success upon execution. Some potential future opportunities for the marketing team include:

  • Survey Data: we would recommend conducting our own customer surveys to grasp their views first-hand, instead of existing coffee shop performance. This can also include measuring our own brand recognition in Ukraine and determining the satisfaction of Ukranian coffee customers with their current options.

  • More Robust Population Analysis: while we touched on population data in this report, looking deeper into the demographics of Ukraine and different urban centers would be extremely valuable in determining the optimal location.

  • Price Analysis: we recommend conducting a more thorough investigation into the pricing of current Ukranian coffee shops. This could include finding the actual price of specific orders at coffee shops, and how our prices compare. Coffee is an extremely elastic market, so pricing is an area we can potentially disrupt.

There were a few issues to work through in the data provided. The most prevalent were:

  • Missing Price Data: of the 200 shops available in the Google Business Reviews, 71 were missing price data. We treated this data as missing, separate from the Expensive, Average, and Cheap possibilities. The shops with missing price data was included in our model, which may have affected accuracy, but was needed with such a small dataset.

  • Missing Delivery Data: we treated shops with missing delivery data as not having a delivery option. This seemed to be the logical solution, as shops who had delivery would likely be included to make sure that was shared online.

  • Data Source: Google Business Reviews data should always be viewed skeptically, as ratings may not fully reflect the experience of each shop.
